^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|An interesting hand. I already discussed why I bid 3C rather than doubling.  West has a clear 3D bid. Anytime your partner opens a weak-2, and you have 3 or more cards in their suit, and 5+ points, you should raise to 3. That is based on the law of total tricks which says you can bid to the level of the number of trumps you have. Here, since West knows they have 9 diamonds, 3D is a safe bid. Always raise to 3 with 3-card support. The only exception is when you have a real good hand and think game is a possibility. Then you can explore with 2N or a new suit. On a majority of hands, however,  raise to 3 with 3-card support. This is known as "furthering the preempt." It is particularly effective had I passed.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to Sandy's bid. It worked out well, but I am not sure I would have bid 3N with her hand. I rate to have a singleton diamond on this auction because Sandy has 3 and they have shown a 9 card fit. Unless I have the DA or DK, or East has both, Sandy rates to lose 6 diamonds off the top. However "no guts no glory" as they say, lol. And Sandy got the glory on this hand. I am not sure Sandy has any good bid. It also turns out that, although East has a clear diamond lead. Had she chosen to lead a heart, 3N is down 1, losing 4 hearts and a diamond. However, that is really not likely nor recommended. Finally, note that, although we have a 4-4 spade fit, we do get a 4-1 break.|
